# Mandatory intake + `changes/` doc workflow

This rule covers THREE chronological touchpoints in every piece of Salesforce work — skip none:

1. **Intake** (work starts) — confirm the ticket / story / case number with the user, and transcribe any acceptance-criteria screenshot or visual source into plain text. The text you capture here is what feeds §3 of the doc later. See [`#intake-protocol`](#intake-protocol).
2. **Pre-coding analysis** (between intake and first code edit) — map the cascading impact of the proposed change BEFORE touching the keyboard: which sObjects, triggers, flows, validation rules, and downstream automation will fire? Which side-effects are intentional vs accidental? Spawn the `changes/<slug>.md` doc early (not at wrap-up) with just the architecture / design-decisions / before-after sections filled from this analysis — that preliminary doc is the working artifact you grow during the work. See [`#pre-coding-analysis-protocol`](#pre-coding-analysis-protocol).
3. **Wrap-up** (work ends) — finalize the doc that's been growing since Step 2, then commit code first and the doc second, with the doc referencing the code commit hash. See [`#wrap-up-protocol`](#wrap-up-protocol).

All three halves are part of the Definition of Done. Don't write code without the intake half, don't write code without the pre-coding analysis half, don't declare work complete without the wrap-up half.

> **Be proactive at all three.** If the user opens a feature/bug with a screenshot or new requirement, pause and run the intake protocol BEFORE writing any code. After intake closes, the NEXT thing you do is the pre-coding analysis — not the code. If work appears wrapped — deploy succeeded, tests pass, a commit just landed, the user said "done" / "looks good" / "works now" / "ready to ship" — surface the wrap-up half and offer to commit the doc that's been growing since pre-coding. Do not wait to be asked at any of the three.

> **Why pre-coding analysis matters.** Salesforce is a heavily-cascading runtime: a single record insert can fire a process builder that fires a flow that fires a trigger that fires a workflow rule that updates a third sObject that fires another trigger. A change that looks like "just create one record" can ripple into 4–5 sObjects, two queueable jobs, and an outbound message — some of those ripples are exactly what the requirement wants, others are accidental and only surface in QA (or worse, in prod). Walking the trigger / flow / validation-rule landscape BEFORE coding catches the accidental ripples while they're still cheap to design around. Discovering them after the code is shipped means rework, regression-bug docs, or worse — silent data drift.

---

## Intake triggers (run the intake protocol)

Run [`#intake-protocol`](#intake-protocol) the FIRST time any of these happen in a conversation:

- The user **attaches a screenshot** of acceptance criteria, a Jira / ADO ticket panel, an email with requirements, a Figma / wireframe link, a Slack thread, a PowerPoint slide, or any other visual source of requirements.
- The user says "let's start <ticket>", "build me <feature>", "I need a fix for <bug>", "new story / requirement / change", "kicking off <story>", or otherwise opens a new piece of work.
- The user gives a verbal/text spec but mentions a ticket / story / case number that's new to the conversation.
- A new chat begins with a feature, bug, or refactor request and the user hasn't already established the ticket context.

> **If you're not sure whether it's a fresh intake**, treat it as one. The cost of asking "confirming this is for <ticket>?" is trivial; the cost of building the wrong scope is huge.

## Pre-coding analysis triggers (run the pre-coding analysis protocol)

Run [`#pre-coding-analysis-protocol`](#pre-coding-analysis-protocol) immediately AFTER the intake protocol closes and BEFORE you open any source file for editing or run any `sf project deploy` / DML command. Specifically:

- The intake protocol (Steps A-D) just finished — the ticket is confirmed, ACs are transcribed, out-of-scope is captured.
- The user has approved the intake bundle and you're about to start working.
- You've already pulled the latest metadata for the touched components per [`retrieve-before-edit`](../../../.claude/skills/retrieve-before-edit/SKILL.md) (if not, do that FIRST — analysis on stale local copies will give wrong answers).
- You're about to add a new sObject record, a new trigger / flow / validation rule, a new Apex class that does DML, a new OmniScript step that calls a DataRaptor or IP, or any change that COULD trigger downstream automation.

> **If the work is genuinely tiny** (a one-line typo fix in a comment, a stub fill, a label rename with no schema implication), the pre-coding analysis collapses to a single sentence in §3 / §5 of the eventual doc — "no downstream automation involved, X.cls comment-only edit". Don't pad. But run the analysis step explicitly so the doc actually has that one-sentence record rather than silently skipping it.

## Wrap-up triggers (run the wrap-up protocol)

Run [`#wrap-up-protocol`](#wrap-up-protocol) the moment any of these happen:

- Final Apex `sf project deploy start ... --test-level RunSpecifiedTests` came back `Succeeded` with all tests passing.
- A real-commit OmniStudio / IP / DataRaptor run produced the expected records and the user confirmed the outcome.
- A `git commit` just completed for `force-app/` changes that close out a ticket.
- The user said "looks good", "works now", "all green", "ready", "done", "ship it", "wrap this up", or similar.
- A pull request is being opened or pushed for the work.
- **An org-wide retrieve run completed** (Phases 0 through 2.22 of [`docs/sf-org-mirror-retrieve.md`](../../docs/sf-org-mirror-retrieve.md)). Use the retrieve template, not bugfix/story/refactor.

If you're unsure whether work is "done", ask the user — don't skip the doc to avoid the question.

