## Intake protocol

When an intake trigger fires, you MUST run **all four steps below** before writing any code, opening any file for editing, or running any `sf` command. Treat the intake as a mandatory checklist; do not collapse it into a single message.

### Step A — Confirm the ticket / story / case number explicitly

State a read-back to the user and wait for confirmation:

> _"Confirming this is for ticket **<TRACKER-NNN>** — _<one-line summary from the screenshot or ask>_. Is that right?"_

Acceptable reference forms:

| Source | Example | Use in doc |
|---|---|---|
| Jira-style | `PROJ-1234`, `STORY-12345` | `**Story / ticket:** [PROJ-1234](<url>) — <summary>` |
| Azure DevOps | `Bug 567890`, `User Story 567890` | `**Story / ticket:** [User Story 567890](<url>) — <summary>` |
| Salesforce Case Id | `500Ov000000XYZ` | `**Source case:** 500Ov000000XYZ — <summary>` |
| Ad-hoc, no tracker | "Sandbox cleanup requested by John on 2026-04-10 over Slack" | `**Source:** Slack request from John (Account Lead), 2026-04-10` |

Rules:
- Do NOT proceed without a confirmed reference. "I'll figure it out later" is forbidden.
- If the user contradicts your read-back, STOP and re-ask. Never silently move forward with a guessed ticket number.
- If the user genuinely has no ticket (rare — usually for ad-hoc cleanup), capture a non-tracker reference per the table above and confirm THAT.

The confirmed reference becomes the value of `**Story / ticket:** ...` in the header block of the changes doc at wrap-up time.

### Step B — Transcribe any AC screenshot / visual source to TEXT

Screenshots and other visual sources are unsearchable, rot when ticket trackers migrate, and don't survive PR review tooling that strips images. The changes doc must be readable a year from now without re-opening Jira. Therefore:

If ANY visual source of requirements was provided (screenshot, Figma frame, wireframe, mockup, email attachment, slide), you MUST:

1. **Read every AC, bullet, or requirement off the image** and write them as numbered plain text — `AC1`, `AC2`, `AC3`, etc.
2. **Post the transcription back to the user in chat** and ask for confirmation: _"Here's what I read off the screenshot — correct me before I start. **AC1**: ... **AC2**: ..."_
3. **Hold the confirmed text in working memory** through the entire piece of work. At wrap-up, it goes verbatim into §3 of the story template (or its equivalent table in bugfix / refactor templates).

A transcription is not optional even if the screenshot is "obvious"; the doc still needs the text form.

> **What counts as a visual source.** ANY of: a Jira / ADO screenshot, a Figma frame URL or export, a wireframe / mockup image, a slide deck snippet, a Lucidchart or whiteboard photo, an email with embedded image, a Salesforce list view screenshot showing expected fields, a comment thread screenshot. If it conveys requirements and isn't already plain text, transcribe it.

### Step C — Capture explicit out-of-scope items

If the ticket / screenshot / spec lists items that are explicitly NOT part of this work ("nice to have, but not now", "follow-up story", "won't fix in this round"), transcribe those into a separate list too. They become the `### Out of scope (explicitly)` block in §3 of the story doc — and prevent scope-creep arguments later.

If no out-of-scope items were called out, ASK the user: _"Anything I should explicitly mark as out-of-scope so it doesn't get bundled into this story by mistake?"_

### Step D — Stash the intake artefacts for wrap-up time

The confirmed ticket reference + transcribed ACs + out-of-scope items form your **intake bundle**. Carry it through the work. When you author `changes/<slug>.md` later, drop the bundle into:

- Header block → `**Story / ticket:** ...` line
- §3 In scope → one row per transcribed AC (Source column references the visual / ticket that originated it)
- §3 Out of scope → bullet list
- §7 Acceptance criteria + verification → one row per AC, with `yes/no` evidence after the work is done

The §3 ACs in the final doc MUST be the transcribed text from Step B — **never** a line that says "see attached screenshot" or "see ticket". A reader of `changes/` should not need any external system open to understand what was agreed to.

