## Pre-coding analysis protocol

After intake closes and BEFORE any code edit, run the five steps below **as TodoWrite entries** (one per step — see Step E0). Each is an explicit, separately-completable unit of work. The protocol's output is a partially-filled `changes/<slug>.md` doc that becomes the working artifact for the rest of the piece of work — you'll grow it during coding and finalize it at wrap-up.

### Step E0 — Spawn the analysis plan as todos FIRST

Before reading any source file or sketching any diagram, spawn a `TodoWrite` plan with one entry per analysis step (E1 through E4 below). Why: like the retrieve workflow (see [`docs/sf-org-mirror-retrieve.md`](../../docs/sf-org-mirror-retrieve.md) §0.0), the pre-coding analysis is a multi-stage sequence that benefits from explicit resumability. If you discover halfway through Step E2 (data-flow mapping) that you need a fresh schema retrieve, the todo list lets you pause, run the retrieve, and resume at the right step instead of losing context.

Minimum required todos:

```
[ ] Step E1 — Identify the touched surface (sObjects, triggers, flows, validation rules, OmniStudio components)
[ ] Step E2 — Map cascading impact (which automation fires on which create / update / delete; build a dependency graph)
[ ] Step E3 — Classify intended vs accidental side-effects (flag the ones to confirm with the user before coding)
[ ] Step E4 — Spawn the preliminary changes/<slug>.md doc and fill the architecture sections from E1-E3 findings
```

Mark each as `in_progress` before starting and `completed` only when its output is actually captured in the preliminary doc.

### Step E1 — Identify the touched surface

List EVERY metadata component the proposed change will read, write, or trigger:

- **sObjects** — what records get created / updated / deleted? Use the schema files (`config/schema/objects/<X>/` per [`salesforce-schema-validation.mdc`](salesforce-schema-validation.mdc)) to confirm field shapes and lookups.
- **Triggers** — `grep -l "<sObject>" force-app/main/default/triggers/*.trigger` to find every trigger on the affected sObject. List by handler class.
- **Flows** — `grep -l "<sObject>" force-app/main/default/flows/*.flow-meta.xml` (look for `<object>` and `<inputAssignments><field>` patterns; record builders / record-triggered flows / scheduled flows are all candidates).
- **Validation rules** — `ls force-app/main/default/objects/<sObject>/validationRules/` lists all rules that fire on insert/update.
- **OmniStudio** — `grep -l "<sObject>" force-app/main/default/omniIntegrationProcedures/*.oip-meta.xml force-app/main/default/omniDataTransforms/*.rpt-meta.xml force-app/main/default/omniScripts/*.os-meta.xml` lists every OmniStudio component that touches the sObject.
- **Apex callers** — `grep -l "<sObject>" force-app/main/default/classes/*.cls` finds classes that DML the sObject.
- **Custom Metadata / Custom Settings** — if any are read for runtime behavior toggles, list them.

Capture the full list in working memory (or scratch notes). It feeds Step E2.

### Step E2 — Map the cascading impact (data-flow sketch)

For each create / update / delete the proposed change will perform, walk the chain DOWNSTREAM:

1. What triggers fire on that DML? (from E1's trigger list)
2. What flows fire on that DML? (from E1's flow list)
3. What downstream DML do those triggers + flows perform — i.e. what OTHER sObjects do they touch?
4. Re-enter step 1 for each newly-touched sObject. Repeat until the chain terminates (no new sObjects touched).

Produce a sketch — a mermaid `flowchart` diagram works well for the eventual doc; for working memory a simple bulleted "A → B → C" tree is enough. Example (generic — substitute your project's sObjects and class names):

```
Account insert
 └─ AccountTrigger
     └─ AccountTriggerHandler.afterInsert
         └─ creates Contact x N (one per linked role)
         └─ Flow `Account After Insert — Set Active__c` updates back to Account
Account update (Active__c true → false)
 └─ Process Builder `Account Inactivation` (legacy)
     └─ Flow `Deactivate Related Contacts` updates all related Contacts
         └─ Contact trigger ContactTrigger
             └─ fires ContactTriggerHandler.afterUpdate
                 └─ updates CountOfActiveContacts__c on parent Account (rollup-style)
```

### Step E3 — Classify intended vs accidental side-effects

Walk the dependency graph from E2 and tag each downstream effect (the example below mirrors the E2 sketch above — substitute your project's sObjects when applying):

| Effect | Tag | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `creates Contact x N` | INTENDED | matches AC3 ("each new Account must spawn one Contact per active role") |
| `Flow updates Active__c back to Account` | INTENDED | matches AC1 (default active=true on creation) |
| `Contact trigger updates CountOfActiveContacts__c rollup on Account` | ACCIDENTAL — flag for confirmation | the AC says nothing about counts; this rollup may bump on every Contact create even when no records are touched directly, possibly racing with the deactivation flow |
| `Process Builder Account Inactivation legacy` | ACCIDENTAL — flag for confirmation | the design assumes triggers only, but a legacy PB is still in the chain — confirm with owner whether to disable it or work around it |

Each ACCIDENTAL row becomes a question to the user / owner before you start coding. Each INTENDED row becomes evidence in the wrap-up doc's §3 (Requirements → AC mapping) or §6 (Architecture). The user has the option to redefine "intended" — never assume a side-effect is OK just because it's already in the org.

> **Anti-pattern**: skipping E3 and "just coding" because the chain looks short. A short chain is exactly when it's cheap to map; long chains often hide cycles that no diagram-less prose can catch.

### Step E4 — Spawn the preliminary `changes/<slug>.md` and fill the architecture sections

Copy the matching template ([per the table below](#pick-a-template)) into `changes/<short-kebab-slug>.md` and **fill the architecture-relevant sections now** from E1-E3 findings. Leave the rest as template placeholders for wrap-up to complete. This is the working artifact the rest of the work grows around.

Which sections to fill per template:

| Template | Architecture sections to fill at Step E4 |
|---|---|
| `_TEMPLATE_bugfix.md` | §3 Architecture / context (the surface from E1 + the chain from E2). §6 Root cause analysis can be filled in skeletal "candidate causes from the dependency chain" form — finalized at wrap-up. |
| `_TEMPLATE_story.md` | §5 Design decisions (alternatives considered, why chosen — the E3 ACCIDENTAL→INTENDED resolution lives here). §6 Architecture (the E2 sketch, ideally as a mermaid `flowchart`). |
| `_TEMPLATE_refactor.md` | §5 Before / after architecture (current state from E1 + E2; intended after-state from the proposed change). §6 Behavioral invariants preserved (each row driven by an E3 INTENDED tag). |

DO NOT commit the preliminary doc yet. It lives as an uncommitted working file through the coding phase. At wrap-up, you fill in the rest of the sections (Implementation summary / Key changes / Verification / Test coverage / etc.) and THEN run the two-commit pattern (code first, then the now-complete doc).

> **Why early creation + late commit?** If you wait to draft the doc at wrap-up, the architecture analysis lives only in your working memory — and gets rewritten from memory hours later, missing the original side-effect classifications. If you commit the preliminary doc early, you fragment the history into 4+ commits per piece of work. The middle path (early write, late commit) keeps the doc structurally complete throughout the work AND collapses to two commits at the end.

> **If the work changes scope mid-flight** (e.g. the user discovers another AC, or the side-effect analysis surfaces a deeper refactor than expected), pause and re-run the relevant E1-E3 steps. Update the preliminary doc's architecture sections. Don't let the doc drift away from reality — its purpose is to lock down "what we're about to do" before each code session, not to recap "what we did" after-the-fact.

### Definition of Done for pre-coding analysis

This protocol is done when ALL of these are true:

1. Step E0-E4 todos are spawned and worked sequentially (no batched-complete).
2. Step E3 has produced an explicit INTENDED-vs-ACCIDENTAL table; the user has confirmed (or you've adjusted the plan based on their answer) any ACCIDENTAL rows.
3. `changes/<slug>.md` exists on disk with the architecture-relevant sections filled (per the §E4 table above). The rest of the doc is still template placeholders — that's expected.
4. The doc is NOT yet committed (the two-commit pattern fires at wrap-up).

