## Wrap-up protocol

Everything from here to "Anti-patterns" governs the wrap-up half: the `changes/<slug>.md` doc, the two-commit strategy, the per-template substance hints, and the generic-adaptation notes for forks. The wrap-up doc draws its requirements (§3) from the intake bundle you captured above.

### Definition of Done

A piece of work is done when ALL of these are true:

1. The intake protocol was run at the start of the work — ticket confirmed, AC text transcribed and confirmed by the user.
2. The pre-coding analysis protocol was run AFTER intake and BEFORE any code edit — the touched surface mapped (E1), cascading impact sketched (E2), intended-vs-accidental side-effects classified and ACCIDENTAL ones confirmed with the user (E3), preliminary `changes/<slug>.md` doc spawned with architecture sections filled (E4).
3. Code/metadata changes deploy cleanly to the working sandbox.
4. Targeted Apex tests pass with the project's required coverage.
5. Apex log retrieved and grepped for hidden `EXCEPTION|ERROR|FATAL` per [`test-deploy-ruleset.mdc`](test-deploy-ruleset.mdc).
6. The two commits exist (see "Two-commit strategy" below): one for code, one for the `changes/` doc.
7. The `changes/<slug>.md` doc — which has been growing as a working artifact since Step E4 — is fully filled in: no stub sections, no `<...>` placeholders left over; §3 contains the transcribed AC text from intake (NOT a screenshot reference); the architecture sections (per the E4 template-mapping table) reflect the FINAL state of the code, not just the pre-coding analysis (update them at wrap-up if implementation diverged).

