## Diff-style highlights (mandatory section in every dev-work template)

The `git diff` between two commits is the canonical record of what changed, but for several Salesforce metadata types it's effectively unreadable:

- **OmniScripts / Integration Procedures / DataRaptors** — XML element trees with auto-generated `propertySet` blobs; the meaningful change is a needle in a haystack.
- **FlexiPages / Page Layouts** — XML hierarchies where a one-property change buries inside hundreds of unchanged lines.
- **Validation rules / Formula fields** — the formula text IS the change, and it's usually wrapped in CDATA which most diff renderers mangle.
- **Profiles / Permission sets** — diff signal is buried under sorted-XML re-orderings that aren't real changes.
- **New Apex classes / triggers** — the entire file is "+" in the diff; a reader can't tell which methods are the actual point of the work.

For these (and for code review more broadly), each dev-work template (bugfix, story, refactor) carries a **"Key changes — diff-style highlights"** section. Use it for ANY change where `git diff` alone won't make a reviewer's job obvious. Two patterns by change size:

### Small / medium changes — inline diff snippet

Paste the meaningful diff in a fenced ```` ```diff ```` block. Trim noise. Add a one-line commentary above it.

```markdown
### N.1 — `OrderProcessing_Procedure_3` — switch which date feeds the activation step

**File:** [`force-app/main/default/omniIntegrationProcedures/OrderProcessing_Procedure_3.oip-meta.xml`](...)
**Type of change:** Modified
**Why:** The activation step should read the order's `Confirmed_Date__c` (when the customer accepts) rather than the auto-populated `CreatedDate` (the record's first-save timestamp). The two differ whenever an order sits in draft for a day or more, and the downstream invoice was using the wrong value.

\```diff
   <element>
     <name>setActivationDate</name>
-    <propertySetConfig>{"dataFrom":"$Steps.OrderLookup.records[0].CreatedDate"}</propertySetConfig>
+    <propertySetConfig>{"dataFrom":"$Steps.OrderLookup.records[0].Confirmed_Date__c"}</propertySetConfig>
   </element>
\```
```

### Large changes (new file, full rewrite, > ~100 lines) — line refs + key method names

```markdown
### N.2 — `OrderActivationService.cls` — NEW class (348 lines)

**File:** [`force-app/main/default/classes/OrderActivationService.cls`](...)
**Type of change:** Created
**Why:** Order activation logic was inlined in the calling OmniScript; pulled it out into a testable service class so other entry points (Apex API, scheduled batch, REST endpoint) can reuse the same activation rules instead of duplicating the flow.

Whole file is too long to paste inline. Key sections:

- Lines 1-25: header + Apex docstring + class declaration with `@SuppressWarnings('PMD.CognitiveComplexity')`.
- Lines 27-78: public entry point `activate(Order__c order)` — the only method other code should call.
- Lines 80-145: private `validateInput(...)`, `loadAccount(...)`, `loadLineItems(...)` — defensive null / inactive-record checks before any DML.
- Lines 147-260: private `applyActivationDates(...)` — fans out across `Order__c`, `OrderItem__c`, and any linked `Contract__c` records; this is the meat of the activation.
- Lines 262-310: private `recordOnAuditTrail(...)` — writes a row to a custom `Activation_Log__c` so admins can see what fired and when.
- Lines 312-348: nested `@TestVisible` data-class wrappers for clean test setup.

See commit `<short-hash>` for the full file; `OrderActivationServiceTest.cls` exercises every public method end-to-end.
```

### When the diff is trivial enough to skip

If the change is 1-2 lines of plain Apex / metadata and `git diff` shows it cleanly without context, the row can collapse to:

```markdown
### N.3 — `MyTrigger.trigger` — one-line guard

**File:** [`...`](...) — see commit `<short-hash>` (1-line addition, `git diff` is sufficient).
```

Don't pad. The point of this section is to surface the changes that AREN'T obvious from diff.

