## Generic adaptation notes (for use in other Salesforce orgs)

This rule is portable. When dropping it (and the templates) into a different Salesforce repo:

1. **Sandbox alias:** the templates use `<sandbox-alias>` placeholder. Set it to whatever your project's default `sf` alias is (check `sf config get target-org`).
2. **Lead name:** customize the `<Name>` placeholder per author. Some teams pre-fill this in the templates.
3. **No org-specific terminology** is baked into the rule or templates. They reference universal Salesforce concepts: Apex, LWC, Aura, OmniStudio, flows, validation rules, profiles, permission sets, custom metadata, `sf` CLI deploy/retrieve/test commands.
4. **`changes/` folder:** the rule assumes `changes/` at repo root. If your project uses a different convention (e.g. `docs/changes/`), update this rule and the templates' relative paths together.
5. **Two-commit strategy:** universal — works in any git repo. The HEREDOC commit-message format works in bash and zsh; PowerShell users need to adjust.
6. **Test coverage thresholds, deploy commands, retrieval rules:** unchanged — the rule defers to `test-deploy-ruleset.mdc` and the project's other Salesforce rules.

For a real worked example of the bug-fix template applied to a real production issue, see [`changes/practitioner-creation-flow-issues.md`](changes/practitioner-creation-flow-issues.md) in this repo. (That example is {{ORG_NAME}}-specific in its content; read it for the **structure**, not the domain content. It will not exist if you drop this ruleset into a different org.)

